COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 151, L.D. 228
1 I. For any seawall that is part of a project involving an increase in the height of seawalls
2 located on 5 or more abutting lots or parcels along the same shoreline, the seawall
3 height increase on all the abutting lots or parcels may not be expected to result in an
4 increase in the extent or intensity of a predicted 100-year flood event on other abutting
5 or adjacent lots that may cause the Federal Emergency Management Agency to revise
6 the relevant flood insurance map to account for that increase, as determined by the
7 department based on a standard engineering analysis provided by the applicant and any
8 other information available to the department.
9 This subsection does not prevent the department from permitting, in accordance with
10 adopted rules, the replacement of an existing seawall with a seawall of different dimensions
11 or in a different location that is further landward if the department determines that the
12 replacement seawall would be less damaging to the coastal sand dune system, existing
13 wildlife habitat and adjacent properties than replacing the existing seawall with a seawall
14 of the same dimensions in the same location.
15 For the purposes of this subsection, "allowable stabilization materials" and "native dune
16 vegetation" have the same meanings as in subsection 15.
17 Sec. 3. 38 MRSA §480-W, sub-§4, as enacted by PL 2005, c. 548, §2, is amended
18 to read:
19 4. Replacement after emergency action under permit by rule. Notwithstanding
20 any other provision of this chapter, the department shall approve a permit by rule to repair
21 or replace a seawall, bulkhead, retaining wall or similar structure that has been destroyed
22 or threatened with a structure that, except as provided in paragraph C, is identical in all
23 dimensions and location as long as a property owner files a completed permit-by-rule
24 notification for the repair or replacement of the structure and the following standards are
25 met:.
26 A. During project construction, disturbance of dune vegetation must be avoided and
27 native vegetation must be retained on the lot to the maximum extent possible. Any
28 areas of dune vegetation that are disturbed must be restored as quickly as possible.
29 Dune vegetation includes, but is not limited to, American beach grass, rugosa rose Rosa
30 virginiana, bayberry, beach pea, beach heather and pitch pine.
31 B. Sand may not be moved seaward of the frontal dune between April 1st and
32 September 1st unless the owner has obtained written approval from the Department of
33 Inland Fisheries and Wildlife.
34 C. The replacement of a seawall may not increase the height, length or thickness of
35 the seawall beyond that which legally existed within the 24 months prior to the
36 submission of the permit-by-rule notification but may increase the height of the seawall
37 in accordance with section 480-E, subsection 19. The replaced seawall may not be
38 significantly different in construction from the one that previously existed.'
39 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
40 number to read consecutively.
41 SUMMARY
4422 This amendment replaces the bill and amends the Natural Resources Protection Act to
4433 authorize the Department of Environmental Protection to approve a permit for a one-time
Page 4 - 132LR0419(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 151, L.D. 228
414 increase by up to 2 feet in the height of a seawall or similar structure in a coastal sand dune
425 system, as long as certain specified conditions are met. The amendment provides a similar
436 allowance for a height increase of up to 2 feet where a seawall has been destroyed or
447 threatened and is replaced after emergency action. It also makes additional clarifications to
458 the provision of the Natural Resources Protection Act regarding coastal sand dune system
469 restoration projects with respect to existing seawalls.
